The Four Core Attack Techniques
1. Spoofed Initial Invitation
Send a METHOD:REQUEST email from an external account with ORGANIZER set to a trusted internal identity. Event auto-appears in victim's calendar and Teams. Victim clicks the meeting link → lands on credential harvesting page.
2. UID Hijacking of Existing Meetings (Lateral Movement)
Post-compromise: read victim's inbox to extract an existing meeting's UID and SEQUENCE. Send a REQUEST update with SEQUENCE+1 — Outlook silently overwrites the original event with attacker-controlled content. The update email is automatically stacked into the existing conversation thread in Trash — nearly invisible.
3. Cancellation-Based Cleanup
Send METHOD:CANCEL with the correct UID — the event disappears from the victim's calendar and the original invite email is moved to Trash. Clean opsec with no manual intervention required.
4. Direct Calendar Injection (No Email Sent)
Using Graph API or CalDAV, write a calendar event directly to a target's mailbox without sending any email. Proofpoint and all email gateways have zero visibility into this — it never touches the email transport layer.

